<div id="review_1052347038" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1052347038" />
    <a title="James Barnard" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/27392963-james-barnard"><img alt="James Barnard" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1052347038?book_show_action=true">Sep 11, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="James Barnard" class="user" itemprop="url" name="James Barnard" href="/user/show/27392963-james-barnard">James Barnard</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/27392963-james-barnard?shelf=crime-and-thriller">crime-and-thriller</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/27392963-james-barnard?shelf=modern-works">modern-works</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1052347038" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8730679705688956114">My enthusiasm for Ruth Rendell novels is always rewarded, and The Bridesmaid is no exception. The familiar tropes are all in place – an awkward young man with an unhealthy interest in an inanimate object, an unhinged young woman, a dysfunctional family, an inept police force and reports of a killer on the loose in the background.<br/><br/>The fact that I could sort of guess what to expect does the novel no harm at all – Rendell has a real talent for wrong-footing the reader and showing that they don’t act</span>
  <span id="freeText8730679705688956114" style="display:none">My enthusiasm for Ruth Rendell novels is always rewarded, and The Bridesmaid is no exception. The familiar tropes are all in place – an awkward young man with an unhealthy interest in an inanimate object, an unhinged young woman, a dysfunctional family, an inept police force and reports of a killer on the loose in the background.<br /><br />The fact that I could sort of guess what to expect does the novel no harm at all – Rendell has a real talent for wrong-footing the reader and showing that they don’t actually know as much as they think they do. Because this is a mystery novel, I’m not going to give too much away. What I will say is that this is a very strong work which stands up with the best of her output.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8730679705688956114" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


