  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1997439624" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1997439624" />
    <a title="Dee Dee" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5565005-dee-dee"><img alt="Dee Dee" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1997439624?book_show_action=true">May 11, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dee Dee" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dee Dee" href="/user/show/5565005-dee-dee">Dee Dee</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer1997439624&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1997439624" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11894331604160045637">I generally really enjoy Rendell. Her use of psychological mystery and the depth of perception she has regarding people and their flaws is something I tend to gravitate toward when reading a mystery. But The Bridesmaid was one of her less enjoyable reads. Without going into detail so as to avoid spoilers, I felt as if Rendell was trying too hard here, something that is not a normal problem for her. Her writing often seems effortless, but not so in this piece.<br/><br/>My largest problem is I got her gist.</span>
  <span id="freeText11894331604160045637" style="display:none">I generally really enjoy Rendell. Her use of psychological mystery and the depth of perception she has regarding people and their flaws is something I tend to gravitate toward when reading a mystery. But The Bridesmaid was one of her less enjoyable reads. Without going into detail so as to avoid spoilers, I felt as if Rendell was trying too hard here, something that is not a normal problem for her. Her writing often seems effortless, but not so in this piece.<br /><br />My largest problem is I got her gist. (Possible spoiler alert) She seems to be painting a picture in which the reader is asked to question who is the maddest person, the one who's incredibly psycho or the one who loves them anyway. She even has a line with the protagonist lamenting women who love serial killers and marry them in prison. Added to that are spurious side stories that cloud the characterization of the protagonist. He is young and impressionable and eventually I think we are to see some sort of redeeming characteristic of the ostensible antagonist through his eyes. <br /><br />I didn't. I just got frustrated because I did not feel that the antagonist had anything to recommend them. Rendell is usually masterful at unlikable characters and they are often excusable just for that fact; they are such awful people that they are perfect as she writes them. Unfortunately often how much was true and how much was false was muddied and convoluted, all the while the protagonist was kind of whiny little baby, upset because his mother was dating, ignoring his sister's addiction until she started borrowing money from him, and resorting to stealing because of his obsession with a family heirloom.<br /><br />These frailties are all supposed to lead to the question if he in fact is the monster, here. He has accepted his fate and supported a deviant murderess basically because they had magnificent sex. <br /><br />I had to drag myself through this one, which makes me sad because when Rendell is good she's amazing.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11894331604160045637" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


